message: Always start by carefully reading and following the provided tips. Most high-scoring items begin with cooking raw ingredients (like beef, fish, eggs, beans, or potatoes) using the 'stove', or soaking 'rice' in 'water', which typically yields items with a value of 20. The key to high scores is then combining 2 or 3 of these *cooked* items. For example, 'cooked beans' with 'cooked soaked rice', or 'cooked potato' with 'cooked soaked rice', often creates items worth 60. Adding a third cooked ingredient, such as 'cooked beef', to a 60-value item can often bring the score to 100. Be very cautious about combining more than 3 cooked items, as this frequently leads to 'overcomplicated' items with significantly reduced or even negative values. Stick to the simpler combinations when aiming for 100.

Adding a single raw vegetable (like mushroom or beet) to this cooked combination can increase the value further. However, be extremely cautious of adding too many ingredients, especially multiple raw vegetables, as this consistently leads to 'overcomplicated' items with significantly negative values. Aim for 2-3 components max for your most valuable item.

message: Focus on cooking all raw ingredients with the stove first. Combining two cooked items (e.g., cooked protein + cooked grain) often yields 60 points. Be very cautious about combining more than three items; adding a fourth cooked ingredient seems to frequently drop the value to 0, creating an 'overcomplicated' item.
